'''Cannabis in California''' is illegal under US [[federal law]], yet legally sanctioned for [[Medical cannabis|medical use]] since 1996, and for [[Recreational drug use|recreational use]] since late 2016. The state of [[California]] has been at the forefront of efforts to liberalize [[legal history of cannabis in the United States|cannabis laws in the United States]], beginning in 1972 with the nation's first ballot initiative attempting to legalize cannabis ([[California Proposition 19 (1972)|Proposition 19]]). Although it was unsuccessful, California would later become the first state to [[Medical cannabis in the United States|legalize medical cannabis]] through the [[Compassionate Use Act of 1996]] (Proposition 215), which passed with 56% voter approval.{{r|BBC}}  In November 2016, California voters approved the [[2016 California Proposition 64|Adult Use of Marijuana Act]] (Proposition 64) with 57% of the vote, which [[Legalization of non-medical cannabis in the United States|legalized the recreational use of cannabis]]. 

As a result of recreational legalization, local governments (city and county) may not prohibit adults from growing, using, or transporting marijuana for personal use. Commercial activities can be regulated or prohibited by local governments although deliveries cannot be prohibited.{{r|LAT 2019-04-05}}{{r|VCS 2019/06/02}} Following recreational legalization, existing growers and suppliers of medical cannabis were required to register, comply with regulations, and apply for permits. Over half of the nonprofit [[Cannabis dispensaries in the United States|dispensaries legally providing medical marijuana]] closed. Local agencies have been slow to approve retail stores selling cannabis for recreational purposes with most cities and counties banning retail with a wait and see approach. Many existing growers have been slow to apply for permits as it has been estimated that 60 percent or more of all cannabis consumed in the United States comes from northern California. The export of marijuana to other states remains illegal since the [[U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration]] considers it a [[Schedule I drug]].

Reducing illegal activity is considered essential for the success of legal operations who pay the considerable taxes assessed by state and local authorities. Many people do not have nearby retail stores selling cannabis and continue to buy from unlicensed sellers. Illegal growing continues in remote rural areas. Raids and confiscation by law enforcement of illegal retail and grow operations have continued and in some cases stepped up after legalization.

California's main regulatory agencies were initially the [[Bureau of Cannabis Control]] (BCC), [[California Department of Food and Agriculture|Department of Food and Agriculture]], and [[California Department of Public Health|Department of Public Health]].{{r|KSBY 2017-11-22}}{{r|Toast}} Their responsibilities were merged under the Department of Cannabis Control in 2021.<ref>[https://cannabis.ca.gov/about-us/consolidation/ State cannabis consolidation]</ref>

== Current state and local regulation ==
Companies must be licensed by the local agency to grow, test, or sell cannabis within each jurisdiction.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nguyen|first=Julia|date=2021-10-27|title=Ventura cannabis company ordered to pay $75k for operating without a license, failure to pay taxes|url=https://keyt.com/news/crime/2021/10/26/ventura-cannabis-company-ordered-to-pay-75k-for-operating-without-a-license-failure-to-pay-taxes/|access-date=2021-10-28|work=KEYT|language=en-US}}</ref> Cities and counties ([[unincorporated area]]s) may license none or only some of these activities.{{r|LAT 2019-04-05}} Deliveries by state-licensed firms cannot be prohibited by local jurisdictions as of January 2019 per BCC Regulation 5416.{{r|VCS 2019/06/02}} A distributor company must work as a middleman between pot producers and retailers.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Black |first=Lester |date=2023-11-19 |title=The biggest pot distributor in California has collapsed |url=https://www.sfgate.com/cannabis/article/failed-california-cannabis-distributor-18496585.php |access-date=2023-11-19 |work=SFGATE |language=en}}</ref>

State agencies were consolidated into the [[California Department of Cannabis Control]] in July 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dolgin|first=Jonathan|date=July 21, 2021|title=California Governor Signs Bill Creating Department of Cannabis Control|url=https://www.jdsupra.com/legalnews/california-governor-signs-bill-creating-1040940/|publisher=Fox Rothschild LLP|via=JD Supra}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bloom |first1=Isabella |title=California opens new marijuana agency 5 years after legalization, aiming to simplify rules |url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article252810093.html |work=The Sacramento Bee |date=July 16, 2021}}</ref> Formerly the industry was under three different state regulatory agencies. Retailers, distributors and testing labs were regulated by the [[California Bureau of Cannabis Control|Bureau of Cannabis Control]]. Cultivators were under the [[California Department of Food and Agriculture|Department of Food and Agriculture]]'s CalCannabis Cultivation Licensing Division. The [[California Department of Public Health|Department of Public Health]]'s Manufactured Cannabis Safety Branch dealt with product manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ocregister.com/newsoms-budget-calls-for-changing-how-california-regulates-its-cannabis-industry|title=Newsom's budget calls for changing how California regulates its cannabis industry|last=Staggs|first=Brooke|date=2020-01-11|newspaper=Orange County Register|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>

Many communities have created zoning regulations to prohibit cannabis stores.  This has led some state legislators to introduce bills that would force many local jurisdictions to allow some retail establishments, especially if a majority in the area voted in favor of legalizing cannabis for recreational purposes.<ref name="LAT 2019-04-05">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-california-sued-pot-deliveries-20190405-story.html|title=California cities sue state over home deliveries of pot|last=McGreevy|first=Patrick|date=April 5, 2019|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> Local governments have been critical of the proposal and were joined by a May 2019 editorial in the [[Los Angeles Times]] that was critical of this type of legislation.<ref name="LAT 2019-05-18">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-marijuana-legalization-proposition-64-local-bans-20190518-story.html|title=California lawmakers already want to roll back a key promise of marijuana legalization|department=The Times Editorial Board|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-05-19}}</ref> State legislators argue that the lack of access to legal establishments is one reason the illegal sales continue.{{r|LAT 2019-04-05}}

California prohibits the export of marijuana to other states since with the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration considers it a Schedule I drug.{{r|LAT 2020-07-04}}<ref>{{Cite web |last=Black |first=Lester |date=2023-12-20 |title=California's latest attempt to save the legal cannabis market just failed |url=https://www.sfgate.com/cannabis/article/california-legal-cannabis-market-rescue-18566778.php |access-date=2023-12-21 |website=SFGATE |language=en}}</ref> California grows up to five times more than its residents consume by some accounts. Others have estimated that 80% of the crop is shipped out of state. Exported cannabis not only escapes taxation or regulation by California but users in other states will pay a much higher price.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-lax-marijuana-trafficking-california-airports-20190512-story.html|title=Weed smuggling arrests at LAX have surged 166% since marijuana legalization|last=Serna|first=Joseph|date=May 12, 2019|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] has investigated officials in several cities and counties.{{r|LAT 2020-11-09}}

Unlicensed sales were not reduced as fast as many expected.<ref name="Yahoo 2019-09-01">{{Cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/californias-legal-pot-industry-is-struggling-against-a-black-market-expert-140029624.html|title=Why California's legal pot industry 'is struggling' against a black market|last=Stratigopoulos|first=McKenzie|date=August 31, 2019|work=Yahoo!| department=Finance|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>{{r|LAT 2019-07-19}} The growth of the legal market has been inhibited since the majority of cities and counties have not allowed the retail sale of cannabis.<ref name="TG 2021-11-02">{{Cite news|last=Lewis|first=Amanda Chicago|date=2021-11-02|title=California legalized weed five years ago. Why is the illicit market still thriving?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/nov/02/california-legal-weed-cannabis-industry-economy|access-date=2021-11-03|work=The Guardian|language=en}}</ref> Due to the continued operation of much illegal activity, heavy taxation is an important issue for licensed operators.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2019-08-23/weedmaps-says-its-going-to-ban-advertisements-from-unlicensed-operators-what-does-that-mean|title=Weedmaps says it will ban advertisements from unlicensed cannabis sellers. Legal sellers applaud|last1=HUSSAIN|first1=SUHAUNA|last2=QUEALLY|first2=JAMES|date=2019-08-24|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref> They are concerned about the perceived lack of sufficient enforcement against illegal activities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article233268053.html|title='Political heavyweights' unite to fight for cannabis from the capitol to the counties|last=Sheeler|first=Andrew|date=August 6, 2019|work=[[Sacramento Bee]]|access-date=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/marijuana/2019/08/22/weedmaps-stop-advertising-unlicensed-pot-businesses/wWhKGkrwtN6FoKkgHbDnpL/story.html|title=Weedmaps to stop advertising unlicensed pot businesses |work=The Boston Globe|last1=Blood|first1=Mike|last2=Johnson|first2=Gene|date=August 22, 2019|agency=Associated Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref> The legal market includes the cost of mandatory testing.{{r|Yahoo 2019-09-01}} Transitioning from a provisional, temporary license to a permanent license has also been difficult. As of April 2020, about 82% of the cannabis licenses were still provisional.<ref>{{Cite news|first= Patrick |last=McGreevy |date=2021-06-14|title=California offers $100 million to rescue its struggling legal marijuana industry|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2021-06-14/california-struggling-marijuana-industry-cash-grants-budget|access-date=2021-06-15|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US}}</ref> Authorities warn that the illegal market may contain pesticide or other chemical residues and mold.{{r|LAT 2019-07-19}} Other products sold illegally that have not been tested include [[cannabis edibles|edible products]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fortunebusinessinsights.com/industry-reports/cannabis-marijuana-market-100219|title=Cannabis Market Size, Research {{!}} Marijuana Industry Growth 2026|date=August 2019|website=Fortune Business Insights|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> and [[electronic cigarettes|vaping pens]].{{r|LAT 2019-09-11}}<ref name="LAT 2019-04-16">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-los-angeles-marijuana-lawsuit-20190416-story.html|title=L.A. sues unlicensed pot dispensary, alleging it sold pesticide-tainted marijuana|last=Queally|first=James|date=April 17, 2019|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref><ref name="LAT 2019-08-25">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-08-25/knockoff-cannabis-products-headache-for-california-legal-weed|title=Counterfeit cannabis products stoke black market for California weed|last=Queally|first=James|date=2019-08-26|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>

=== Possession ===
Local governments may not prohibit adults from growing, using or transporting marijuana for personal use. An appeals court ruled that inmates who possess small amounts of marijuana in prison are not guilty of a felony crime.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/16/us/california-inmates-marijuana.html|title=Inmates Can Legally Possess Marijuana, but Not Smoke It, California Court Rules|last=Taylor|first=Derrick Bryson|date=2019-06-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Attorney General [[Xavier Becerra]]'s office had argued that possessing small amounts of marijuana is legally banned in prison which can result in significantly increasing a prisoner's sentence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/06/14/732730429/possessing-marijuana-in-prison-is-not-a-felony-california-court-says|title=Possessing Marijuana In Prison 'Is Not A Felony,' California Court Says|work=NPR News|first=Bill|last=Chappel|date=June 14, 2019|language=en|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>

=== Cultivation ===
Cannabis is estimated to be the largest cash crop in California with a value of more than $11 billion.<noinclude>{{r|CBS 2020-08-02}}</noinclude><includeonly><ref name="CBS 2020-08-02" /></includeonly> The state provided most of the cannabis consumed in the United States prior to legalization which was intended to provide a transition to legal, licensed growing. The [[California Environmental Quality Act]] (CEQA) requires a detailed [[Environmental impact assessment|analysis of the environmental impact]] of growers operations. Statewide, 208 growers had obtained regular, annual licenses by July 2019. At this point of some 18 months into legalization, 1,532 growers were still operating on provisional permits as they went through the CEQA process that requires extensive paperwork.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-pot-business-permits-delayed-20190614-story.html|title=California to give struggling cannabis businesses more time on provisional permits|last=McGreevy|first=Patrick|date=June 14, 2019|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref> Smaller farms were given five years to become established under legalization before larger growers were allowed to enter the market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/story/2020-02-11/cannabis-farms-california-agriculture-regulations|title=Op-Ed: Get Big Agriculture out of cannabis farming in California|last=Polson|first=Michael|date=2020-02-11|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> Under the regulations set to expire in 2023, growers can have only one medium licence but there is no limit on the number of small licenses an individual grower can have. This [[loophole]] has allowed larger growers to operate.{{r|VCS 2018/04/29}}

[[Humboldt County, California|Humboldt]], [[Mendocino County|Mendocino]], and [[Trinity County, California|Trinity]] counties have long been known as Northern California's [[Emerald Triangle]] as it is estimated that 60 percent or more of all cannabis consumed in the United States is grown there. Registering and applying for permits has not been an easy decision for many long time growers in these three counties.<ref name="CBS 2020-08-02">{{Cite news|last=Alfonsi|first=Sharyn|date=August 2, 2020|title=How red tape and black market weed are buzzkills for California's legal marijuana industry|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/marijuana-in-california-black-market-weed-buzzkills-for-california-legal-weed-industry-60-minutes-2020-08-02/|access-date=2020-08-03|work=CBS News|language=en-US}}</ref>

In [[Santa Barbara County]], cannabis growing has taken over greenhouses that formerly grew flowers. In the first four months of legalization, the county had almost 800 permits issued for cultivators, the most of any county in the state.<ref name="VCS 2018/04/29">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vcstar.com/story/news/2018/04/29/santa-barbara-county-leads-california-number-permits-legally-grow-marijuana/562364002/|title=Santa Barbara County leads California in the number of permits to legally grow marijuana|last=Staggs|first=Brooke|date=April 28, 2018|newspaper=[[Ventura County Star]]|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190908220945/https://www.vcstar.com/story/news/2018/04/29/santa-barbara-county-leads-california-number-permits-legally-grow-marijuana/562364002/|archive-date=2019-09-08|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Calaveras County, California|Calaveras County]] registered more than seven hundred cultivators after county voters approved a tax in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-calaveras-county-marijuana-20180228-htmlstory.html|title=A rural county legalized marijuana farms. It took their tax money – then voted to ban them|last=Parvini|first=Sarah|date=2018-02-28|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>

==== Trespass grows ====
Unlicensed growing continues in remote rural areas and has expanded according to law enforcement reports. Raids and confiscation of illegal grow operations by law enforcement has continued and in some cases stepped up after legalization.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-marijuana-raids-riverside-county-20190605-story.html|title=Illegal pot growers targeted by Riverside County officials in second raid in 6 weeks|last=Shalby|first=Colleen|date=June 5, 2019|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sanluisobispo.com/news/local/crime/article231866238.html|title=Raids turn up 40,000 pounds of marijuana, 350,000 plants in SLO, Santa Barbara counties|last=Bolton|first=Tom|date=June 22, 2019|newspaper=[[San Luis Obispo Tribune]]|language=en|access-date=2019-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Blood|first=Michael R.|date=2020-07-16|title=Report: Pot arrests still fall heavily on Hispanics, Blacks|url=https://apnews.com/02383a8dcf7fbbef3b876c20a587b709|access-date=2020-08-06|work=AP NEWS}}</ref> Authorities are constantly dealing with illegal cultivation in remote protected areas such as state parks and national forests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/environment/story/2019-08-21/mexican-marijuana-traffickers-banned-pesticide-carbofuran-california-forests|title=Mexican marijuana traffickers are poisoning California forests with a banned pesticide, officials say|last=McDaniel|first=Piper|date=2019-08-21|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Nobert |first=Matthew |date=2024-07-11 |title=Over 2,000 lbs of illegal cannabis grow waste found in Northern California's largest state park |url=https://fox40.com/news/california-connection/over-2000-lbs-of-illegal-cannabis-grow-waste-found-in-northern-californias-largest-state-park/ |access-date=2024-07-12 |website=FOX40 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/12/773122043/illegal-pot-grows-in-americas-public-forests-are-poisoning-wildlife-and-water|title=Illegal Pot Operations In Public Forests Are Poisoning Wildlife And Water|last=Westervelt|first=Eric|date=November 12, 2019|work=NPR News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> Illegal grows are partially responsible for record levels of water thefts during the [[Droughts in California|drought that began in 2020]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cart|first=Julie|date=2021-07-20|title=Thieves are stealing California's scarce water. Where's it going? Illegal marijuana farms|url=https://calmatters.org/environment/2021/07/illegal-marijuana-growers-steal-california-water/|access-date=2021-07-21|work=CalMatters|language=en-US}}</ref>

