==== Pests and diseases ====
{{See also|Cannabis pests|Cannabis diseases|Hemp pests|Hemp diseases}}
A large number of [[insect pest]]s are significant, along with some mammals: [[Mice]], ''[[Rattus rattus]]'', ''[[Neotoma]]'' rat spp., ''[[Thomomys]]'' gopher spp., [[black-tailed deer]] (''Odocoileus hemionus columbianus''), and black bears (''[[Ursus americanus]]'').<ref name="Ca-Dept-Pesti-Reg-2017">{{cite web | url=http://www.cdpr.ca.gov/docs/county/cacltrs/penfltrs/penf2015/2015atch/attach1502.pdf | title=Legal Pest Management Practices for Cannabis Growers in California | date=October 9, 2017 | author=[[California Department of Pesticide Regulation]] | pages=1{{endash}}8}}</ref> Powdery mildew ''[[Sphaerotheca macularis]]'' and various Pythium root rots (''[[Pythium]]'' spp.) are important [[List of hemp diseases|diseases in this crop]].<ref name="Ca-Dept-Pesti-Reg-2017" /> The [[Department of Pesticide Regulation]] provides legal guidance and treatment recommendations for all of these.<ref name="Ca-Dept-Pesti-Reg-2017" />

=== On-site consumption ===
In July 2019, [[West Hollywood]] approved a cannabis consumption license for [[Lowell Herb Co]], "the first of its kind in the nation". [[Lowell Farms: A Cannabis Cafe]] opened in September 2019 with a menu of cannabis for consumption, THC-infused drinks and meals for cannabis-enhanced sense of taste and smell. It includes the expertise of cannabis [[sommelier]]s, known as "[[budtender]]s" on site.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-07-17/first-cannabis-cafe-west-hollywood|title=First cannabis cafe approved by West Hollywood, but local rabbi isn't happy|last=Reyes-Velarde|first=Alejandra|date=2019-07-17|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/america-s-first-cannabis-caf-open-la-1223835 |title=America's First Cannabis Café Featuring 'Budtenders' to Open in L.A. |last=Schmidt |first=Ingrid |date=2019-07-11 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en |access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref> It has since been rebranded as the "Original Cannabis Cafe", separating itself from the Lowell Farms corporate brand. A retail establishment Seaweed On Ocean, was licensed in [[Lompoc]] for on site consumption in July 2018 and opened December 2019, claims to be the first between Los Angeles and San Francisco.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ksby.com/news/local-news/new-cannabis-shop-opening-in-lompoc-to-offer-on-site-consumption|title=New cannabis shop opening in Lompoc to allow on-site consumption|date=2019-12-12|work=KSBY|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>

=== Retail and delivery ===
Stores selling cannabis for recreational purposes have been banned from 80% of the 482 municipalities in California.{{r|LAT 2019-04-05}} In September 2019, 873 cannabis sellers had been licensed by the state while the United Cannabis Business Assn. conducted an audit that estimated there are approximately 2,835 unlicensed dispensaries and delivery services based on advertising.<ref name="LAT 2019-09-11">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-09-11/california-marijuana-black-market-dwarfs-legal-pot-industry|title=Nearly 3,000 illegal marijuana businesses found in California audit, dwarfing legal trade|last1=Queally|first1=James|last2=McGreevy|first2=Patrick|date=2019-09-12|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> Legal retailers say the illegal market is larger than the legal market due to the high costs they pay in start-up permit costs and on-going taxes. They complain about the lack of effective enforcement against unlicensed shops.{{r|CBS 2020-08-02}}

Prior to 2018, about 2,000 nonprofit dispensaries legally provided medical marijuana. Legalization introduced regulations that increased the cost of operation and more than 65% of dispensaries shut their doors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-deangelo-marijuana-cannabis-tax-deductions-20190715-story.html|title=How the U.S. tax code keeps the illegal market for marijuana alive and well|last=DeAngelo|first=Steve|date=July 15, 2019|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref> Recreational marijuana shops began to open in January 2018, with many districts beginning recreational sales on the first or fifth of January 2018.<ref name=kpcc>{{cite news|last1=Margolis|first1=Jacob|title=California Report: 6 Ways Recreational Pot Would Change California — and 7 Ways It Wouldn't|url=http://elections.kqed.org/article/marijuana/11076610/6-ways-recreational-pot-would-change-california-and-7-ways-it-wouldnt|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105161152/http://elections.kqed.org/article/marijuana/11076610/6-ways-recreational-pot-would-change-california-and-7-ways-it-wouldnt|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 November 2016|access-date=4 November 2016|work=[[KPCC (radio station)|KPCC]]|date=6 September 2016}}</ref> In January, 2018, Los Angeles had no licensed retailers; the closest cities with licensed retail sales were [[Santa Ana, California|Santa Ana]] on January 1 and [[West Hollywood]] on January 2.<ref>{{citation|title=California pot shops prepare for their first day of legal recreational marijuana sales|author1=Angel Jennings |author2=Sarah Parvini|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 31, 2017|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-marijuana-prep-20171231-story.html}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=LA Begins Pot Licensing Process|date=January 3, 2018|publisher=CBS Los Angeles |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2018/01/03/la-begins-pot-licensing-process/}}</ref> {{As of|2019|September}}, 187 dispensaries had temporary city approval in Los Angeles.{{r|LAT 2019-09-11}}  Los Angeles adopted an ordinance in 2018 to restrict some storefront and billboard advertising after research showed that young adults who lived near dispensaries that had storefront signage used marijuana more frequently than their peers and have more positive views about the drug.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-marijuana-pot-dispensary-young-people-20190617-story.html|title=Living near marijuana dispensaries makes youth more likely to use it, study finds|date=2019-06-18|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>

Many dispensaries and delivery companies continued to operate under the [[stay-at-home order]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/money/business/2020/03/23/cannabis-sales-spike-during-california-shelter-place/2885930001/|title='Essential' cannabis companies are seeing sales spikes during California's shelter-in-place order|last=Daniels|first=Melissa|date=May 24, 2020|work=Desert Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> With an executive order on March 22, Governor Gavin Newsom declared cannabis one of the enterprises to be considered an essential business.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-18/california-north-states-cannabis-industry-jackpot|title=Boom times for cannabis businesses as Californians, in a pandemic fog, isolate indoors|last1=Rust|first1=Susanne|last2=Cole|first2=Carolyn|date=2020-04-18|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>

=== Special events ===
Organizers of cannabis festivals are required to get permission from state and local agencies. Under the permits, they can let anyone 21 and older buy and smoke weed at the festival.<ref name="DB 2019-05-03">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sbsun.com/ice-cube-to-headline-first-licensed-cannabis-cup-marijuana-festival-in-southern-california|title=Ice Cube to headline first licensed Cannabis Cup marijuana festival in Southern California|last=Staggs|first=Brooke Edwards|date=2019-05-03|newspaper=Daily Breeze|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-08-11/outside-lands-cannabis-sales-music-festival|title=A whiff of the music festival future? Outside Lands sells cannabis for the first time|last1=Chabria|first1=Anita|last2=McGreevy|first2=Patrick|date=2019-08-12|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> In 2019, [[Outside Lands Music and Arts Festival]] in San Francisco became the first major music festival to offer legal cannabis for sale on site. The area was known as "Grass Lands" and sold more than $1 million in cannabis products such as edibles, vaping cartridges and joints over the three-day event.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Outside-Lands-Grass-Lands-total-marijuana-sold-14304264.php |title=Outside Lands' Grass Lands sold seven figures worth of cannabis. How much weed is that? |last=Gentile |first=Dan |date=2019-08-14 |work=SFGate |access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>

== History ==
=== Industrial hemp ===
[[Cannabis]] was cultivated for fiber and rope as early as 1795 in California, when cultivation began at [[Mission San José (California)|Mission San Jose]] under the governorship of [[Diego de Borica]]. Cannabis was grown in several regions of Southern California, with two-thirds of it being grown on the missions.<ref name="ClarkeMerlin2013">{{cite book|author1=Robert Clarke|author2=Mark Merlin|title=Cannabis: Evolution and Ethnobotany|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=poenY6QMq8UC&pg=PA181|date=1 September 2013|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-95457-1|pages=181–}}</ref> California produced 13,000 pounds of hemp in 1807, and 220,000 pounds in 1810.<ref name="Incorporated2008">{{cite book|author=Facts On File, Incorporated|title=Marijuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=knyWvsS9-BIC&pg=PA46|year=2008|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-1824-6|pages=46–}}</ref> However, in 1810 Mexico began to rebel against the Spanish crown, and the subsidies for growing hemp were cut, leading to a near-disappearance of the crop. A few missions continued to grow it for local use, and the [[Russian colonization of the Americas|Russian colonists]] grew hemp at [[Fort Ross]] until the station was abandoned in 1841.<ref name="ClarkeMerlin2013"/>

=== Psychoactive cannabis ===
Among the early cultivators of cannabis for recreational use in California were Arabs, Armenians, and Turks who grew cannabis as early as 1895 to make [[hashish]] for local consumption.<ref name="Duvall2014">{{cite book|author=Chris Duvall|title=Cannabis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SVU8BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT99|date=15 November 2014|publisher=Reaktion Books|isbn=978-1-78023-386-4|pages=99–}}</ref> Unlike in other states where fears of black or Hispanic use of cannabis drove new restrictions, California was an exception for its focus on South Asian immigrants. A California delegate to the Hague Convention wrote in 1911: ''Within the last year we in California have been getting a large influx of Hindoos and they have in turn started quite a demand for cannabis indica; they are a very undesirable lot and the habit is growing in California very fast.''<ref name="Booth2015">{{cite book|author=Martin Booth|title=Cannabis: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ecITBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA163|date=16 June 2015|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-250-08219-0|pages=163–}}</ref>

=== Criminalization ===
The Poison Act was passed in California in 1907, and in 1913 an amendment<ref>([http://192.234.213.35/clerkarchive/archive/Statutes/1913/1913.pdf Stats. 1913] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112060204/http://192.234.213.35/clerkarchive/archive/Statutes/1913/1913.pdf |date=2013-11-12 }}, Ch. 342, p.&nbsp;697)</ref> was made to make possession of "extracts, tinctures, or other narcotic preparations of hemp, or loco-weed, their preparations and compounds" a misdemeanor.<ref name="gieringer">{{cite journal |last=Gieringer |first=Dale H. |year=1999 |title=The Forgotten Origins of Cannabis Prohibition in California |url=https://www.canorml.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Cal-Origins-MJ-Proh-2024.pdf |journal=Contemporary Drug Problems |volume=26 |issue=2 |pages=237–288 |doi=10.1177/009145099902600204 |s2cid=145499009}}</ref> There is no evidence that the law was ever used or intended to restrict pharmaceutical cannabis; instead it was a legislative mistake, and in 1915 another amendment<ref>([http://192.234.213.35/clerkarchive/archive/Statutes/1915/15Vol1_Chapters.pdf Stats. 1915] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112060309/http://192.234.213.35/clerkarchive/archive/Statutes/1915/15Vol1_Chapters.pdf |date=2013-11-12 }}, Ch. 604, pp.&nbsp;1067–1068)</ref> forbade the sale or possession of "flowering tops and leaves, extracts, tinctures and other narcotic preparations of hemp or loco weed (''Cannabis sativa''), Indian hemp" except with a prescription.<ref name="gieringer"/> Both bills were drafted and supported by the California State Board of Pharmacy.<ref name="gieringer"/>

In 1914, one of the first cannabis drug raids in the nation occurred in the Mexican-American neighborhood of [[Sonoratown]] in Los Angeles, where police raided two "dream gardens" and confiscated a wagonload of cannabis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scpr.org/programs/offramp/2014/09/19/39399/the-nation-s-first-marijuana-raid-likely-happened/|title=The nation's first marijuana raid likely happened in LA|date=September 19, 2014|website=Southern California Public Radio}}</ref> In 1925, possession, which had previously been treated the same as distribution, became punishable by up to 6 years in prison, and black market sale, which had initially been a misdemeanor punishable by a $100–$400 fine and/or 50–180 days in jail for first offenders, became punishable by 6 months–6 years.<ref name="gieringer"/> In 1927, the laws designed to target opium usage were finally extended to Indian hemp.<ref name="gieringer"/> In 1929, second offenses for possession became punishable by sentences of 6 months–10 years.<ref name="gieringer"/> In 1937, cannabis cultivation became a separate offense.<ref name="gieringer"/>

By 1932, 60% of narcotics arrests in Los Angeles involved cannabis, which was considered "much less serious than the morphine cases."<ref>{{cite book|title=Survey of Drug Addiction in California|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zQF4YCdtz7AC|year=1932|publisher=California state printing office, H. Hammond, state printer}}</ref> In 1954, penalties for marijuana possession were hiked to a minimum 1–10 years in prison, and sale was made punishable by 5–15 years with a mandatory 3 years before eligibility for parole; two prior felonies raised the maximum sentences for both offenses to life imprisonment.<ref name="gieringer"/>

=== Popularization ===
In the 1950s and 1960s, the beatnik and later hippie cultures experimented with cannabis, driving increased interest in the drug. In 1964, the first cannabis legalization group was formed in the U.S. when Lowell Eggemeier of San Francisco was arrested, and his attorney established LEMAR (LEgalize MARijuana) shortly afterwards.<ref name="Rosenthal2009">{{cite book|author=Ed Rosenthal|title=Marijuana Grower's Handbook: Your Complete Guide for Medical and Personal Marijuana Cultivation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ySRFAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT20|date=1 July 2009|publisher=Quick Trading Company|isbn=978-0-932551-50-4|pages=20–}}</ref> By the mid-1960s, the ''Saturday Evening Post'' was publishing articles estimating that half the college population of California had tried cannabis. One writer commented that usage was: ''so widespread that pot must be considered an integral part of the generation's life experience.''<ref name="May2002">{{cite book|author=Kirse Granat May|title=Golden State, Golden Youth: The California Image in Popular Culture, 1955-1966|url=https://archive.org/details/goldenstategolde0000mayk|url-access=registration|year=2002|publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press|isbn=978-0-8078-5362-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/goldenstategolde0000mayk/page/189 189]–}}</ref>

=== Illicit cultivation ===
In the 1960s–1970s, people in California had developed the ''[[sinsemilla]]'' ("without seeds") method of producing cannabis, uprooting the male plants before they could pollinate the females, resulting a seedless and more potent cannabis. Around 1975, this technique arrived in Humboldt County, which was to become one of the nation's most famous centers of cannabis production. California growers received an unintentional advantage from the US government, which in the 1970s began spraying cannabis fields in Mexico with the herbicide [[paraquat]]. Fears of contamination led to a drop in demand for cheaper Mexican cannabis, and a corresponding increase in demand for California-grown cannabis. By 1979, 35% of cannabis consumed in California was grown in-state. By 2010, 79% of cannabis nationwide came from California.<ref name="Brady2013">{{cite book|author=Emily Brady|title=Humboldt: Life on America's Marijuana Frontier|url=https://archive.org/details/humboldtlifeonam0000brad|url-access=registration|date=18 June 2013|publisher=Grand Central Publishing|isbn=978-1-4555-0677-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/humboldtlifeonam0000brad/page/55 55]–}}</ref>

=== Decriminalization ===
{{broader|Decriminalization of non-medical cannabis in the United States}}

==== Moscone Act (1975) ====
[[Decriminalization]] of cannabis{{snd}}which treats possession of small amounts as a civil (rather than a criminal) offense{{snd}}was established in July 1975 when the state legislature passed Senate Bill 95, the Moscone Act.<ref name="gieringer"/><ref name="Anderson" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/publications/Abstract.aspx?id=45532|title=IMPACT OF CALIFORNIA'S NEW MARIJUANA LAW (SB 95) REPORT, 1ST|last=Budman|first=K B|access-date=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref name="Crime">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ahzoZhXyQwC&q=California+%22SB+95%22+marijuana&pg=PA249|title=Crime: Critical Concepts in Sociology|publisher=Routledge|year=2003|isbn=978-0-415-25267-6|pages=249–250|access-date=January 15, 2010|editor=Philip Bean}}</ref> SB 95 made possession of {{convert|1|oz|g|spell=in}} of marijuana a misdemeanor punishable by a $100 fine, with higher punishments for amounts greater than one ounce, for possession on school grounds, or for cultivation.<ref name="NORML">{{cite web|url=http://www.norml.com/index.cfm?wtm_view=&Group_ID=4525|title=California - NORML|publisher=National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws (NORML)|access-date=January 15, 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100112181026/http://norml.com/index.cfm?wtm_view=&Group_ID=4525|archive-date=January 12, 2010}}</ref>

==== "Smoke a joint, lose your license" expires (1999) ====
{{Broader|Solomon–Lautenberg amendment}}
In 1999, a state law was allowed to expire that mandated a six-month driver's license suspension for possession of cannabis or other illegal drugs.<ref name="davis">{{cite news |last1=Bustillo |first1=Miguel |title=Davis Fights to Suspend Licenses in Drug Cases |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2000-may-24-mn-33499-story.html |access-date=September 20, 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=May 24, 2000}}</ref> The law was enacted in 1994 at the urging of Governor [[Pete Wilson]], who argued that the policy kept unsafe drivers off the road and helped prevent illegal drug use.<ref name="wilson">{{cite news |last1=Ingram |first1=Carl |title='Smoke a Joint, Lose License' Law in Effect |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1994-12-01-mn-3616-story.html |access-date=September 20, 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=December 1, 1994}}</ref> Critics argued that the punishment was excessive and often had nothing to do with the offense committed.<ref name="wilson" /> The law resulted in as many as 100,000 license suspensions per year according to the [[California Department of Motor Vehicles]].<ref name="davis" />

==== Proposition 36 (2000) ====
{{main|California Proposition 36 (2000)}}
Proposition 36 (also known as the Substance Abuse and Crime Prevention Act of 2000) was approved by 61% of voters, requiring that "first and second offense drug violators be sent to drug treatment programs instead of facing trial and possible incarceration."<ref name="Prop36">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2000/11/15/MN108231.DTL|title=Money, Opinion Propelled Prop. 36|last=Wallace|first=Bill|date=November 15, 2000|work=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=January 15, 2010}}</ref>

==== Senate Bill 1449 (2010) ====
On September 30, 2010, Governor [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] signed into law CA State Senate Bill 1449, which further reduced the charge of possession of {{convert|1|oz|g|spell=in}} of cannabis or less, from a misdemeanor to an infraction, similar to a traffic violation—a maximum of a $100 fine and no mandatory court appearance or criminal record.<ref name="activatedirect1">{{Cite web|url=http://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billNavClient.xhtml?bill_id=200920100SB1449|title=Bill Text - SB-1449 Marijuana: possession.|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov}}</ref> The law became effective January 1, 2011.

=== Medical cannabis legalization ===
==== Early reform efforts (pre-1996) ====
The movement to legalize medical cannabis in the U.S. sprang out of [[San Francisco]] in the early 1990s, with efforts soon spreading statewide and eventually across the nation.  Proposition P was approved by 79% of San Francisco voters in November 1991, calling on state lawmakers to pass legislation allowing the medical use of cannabis.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boire|first1=Richard Glen|last2=Feeney|first2=Kevin|title=Medical Marijuana Law|date=January 26, 2007|publisher=Ronin Publishing|isbn=9781579510343|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c1Tw_UFU2XEC}}</ref>  The city board of supervisors additionally passed a resolution in August 1992 urging the police commission and district attorney to "make lowest priority the arrest or prosecution of those involved in the possession or cultivation of [cannabis] for medicinal purposes" and to "allow a letter from a treating physician to be used as [[Prima facie|prima facia]] evidence that marijuana can alleviate the pain and suffering of that patient's medical condition".<ref>{{cite web|title=Proposition P|url=http://www.marijuanalibrary.org/Proposition_P_Nov_1991.html|website=marijuanalibrary.org|access-date=April 30, 2017}}</ref>  The resolution enabled the open sale of cannabis to AIDS patients and others within the city, most notably through the [[San Francisco Cannabis Buyers Club]] which was operated by medical cannabis activist [[Dennis Peron]] (who spearheaded Proposition P and later the statewide Proposition 215).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gardner|first1=Fred|title=The Cannabis Buyers Club: How Medical Marijuana Began in California|url=https://www.marijuana.com/news/2014/08/the-cannabis-buyers-club-how-medical-marijuana-began-in-california/|access-date=May 4, 2017|work=marijuana.com|date=August 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120221138/https://www.marijuana.com/news/2014/08/the-cannabis-buyers-club-how-medical-marijuana-began-in-california/|archive-date=November 20, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Similar clubs appeared outside San Francisco in the ensuing years as other cities passed legislation to support the medical use of cannabis.  The [[Wo/Men's Alliance for Medical Marijuana]] was founded in 1993 after 75% of [[Santa Cruz, California|Santa Cruz]] voters approved Measure A in November 1992.<ref name="Heddleston">{{cite thesis|last1=Heddleston|first1=Thomas R.|title=From the Frontlines to the Bottom Line: Medical Marijuana, the War on Drugs, and the Drug Policy Reform Movement|url=http://escholarship.org/uc/item/1t7220hj|publisher=UC Santa Cruz Electronic Theses and Dissertations|date=June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019053506/http://escholarship.org/uc/item/1t7220hj|archive-date=October 19, 2015|url-status=live}} [https://archive.org/details/MedicalMarijuanaTheWarOnDrugsAndTheDrugPolicyReformMovement Alt URL]</ref>  And the [[Oakland Cannabis Buyers' Cooperative]] was founded in 1995 shortly before the city council passed multiple medical cannabis resolutions.<ref name="Heddleston" />

Following the lead of San Francisco and other cities in California, state lawmakers passed Senate Joint Resolution 8 in 1993, a non-binding measure calling on the federal government to enact legislation allowing physicians to prescribe cannabis.<ref name="Vitiello 215">{{cite news|last1=Vitiello|first1=Michael|title=Proposition 215: De Facto Legalization of Pot and the Shortcomings of Direct Democracy|url=http://scholarlycommons.pacific.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1093&context=facultyarticles|access-date=April 30, 2017|publisher=McGeorge School of Law|date=1998}}</ref>  In 1994, Senate Bill 1364 was approved by state legislators, to reclassify cannabis as a Schedule II drug at the state level.<ref name="Vitiello 215" />  And Assembly Bill 1529 was approved in 1995, to create a medical necessity defense for patients using cannabis with a physician's recommendation, for treatment of AIDS, cancer, glaucoma, or multiple sclerosis.<ref name="Vitiello 215" />  Both SB 1364 and AB 1529 were vetoed by Governor [[Pete Wilson]], however, paving the way for the passage of Proposition 215 in 1996.<ref name="Vitiello 215" />

==== Proposition 215 (1996) ====
{{main|1996 California Proposition 215}}
Frustrated by vetoes of medical cannabis bills in successive years, medical cannabis advocates in California took the issue directly to the voters, collecting 775,000 signatures for qualification of a statewide ballot initiative in 1996.<ref>{{cite news|title=Medical Marijuana Initiative Qualifies For November Ballot|url=http://norml.org/news/1996/06/06/medical-marijuana-initiative-qualifies-for-november-ballot|access-date=April 30, 2017|work=NORML|date=June 6, 1996}}</ref>  Proposition 215{{snd}}the Compassionate Use Act of 1996{{snd}}was subsequently approved with 56% of the vote, legalizing the use, possession, and cultivation of cannabis by patients with a physician's recommendation, for treatment of cancer, anorexia, AIDS, chronic pain, spasticity, glaucoma, arthritis, migraine, or "any other illness for which marijuana provides relief".<ref name="Prop215 text">{{cite web|title=Proposition 215: Text of Proposed Law|url=http://medicalmarijuana.procon.org/sourcefiles/california-proposition-215.pdf|website=ProCon.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517131727/http://medicalmarijuana.procon.org/sourcefiles/california-proposition-215.pdf|archive-date=May 17, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The law also allowed patient [[caregiver]]s to cultivate cannabis, and urged lawmakers to facilitate the "safe and affordable distribution of marijuana".<ref name="Prop215 text" />

==== Senate Bill 420 (2003) ====
{{Main|California Senate Bill 420}}
[[File:Medical-cannabis-card-california.jpg|thumb|right|Medical cannabis card in [[Marin County, California|Marin County]]]]

Vague wording became a major criticism of Proposition 215, though the law has since been clarified through state Supreme Court rulings and the passage of subsequent laws. The first such legislative solution came in January 2003 with the passage of Senate Bill 420 (colloquially known as the Medical Marijuana Program Act).  Senate Bill 420 established an [[Medical cannabis card|identification card system for medical cannabis patients]], and allowed the formation of non-profit collectives for provision of cannabis to patients.

In 2006 [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]] filed a lawsuit over its required participation in the state ID card program,<ref>{{cite news|last1=McDonald|first1=Jeff|title=County pursues medicinal marijuana case|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-county-pursues-medicinal-marijuana-case-2008oct27-story.html|access-date=March 7, 2018|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|date=October 27, 2008}}</ref> but the challenge was later struck down and the city was forced to comply.<ref name="Lee" /> In January 2010 the California Supreme Court ruled in ''[[California Senate Bill 420#People v. Kelly|People v. Kelly]]'' that SB 420 did not limit the quantity of cannabis that a patient can possess.  All possession limits were therefore lifted.

==== Implementation and criticism ====
California was the first state to establish a medical cannabis program, enacted by Proposition 215 in 1996 and Senate Bill 420 in 2003. Proposition 215, also known as the Compassionate Use Act, allows people the right to obtain and use cannabis for any illness if they obtain a recommendation from a doctor. The [[Supreme Court of California]] has ruled there are no specified limits as to what a patient may possess in their private residence if the cannabis is strictly for the patient's own use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.canorml.org/news/supremekelly.html|title=Ca Supreme Court Strikes Down Medical Marijuana Possession, Cultivation Limits|website=www.canorml.org|date=January 21, 2010|access-date=2016-11-10}}</ref> Medical cannabis identification cards are issued through the [[California Department of Public Health]]'s Medical Marijuana Program (MMP). The program began in three counties in May 2005, and expanded statewide in August of the same year. 37,236 cards have been issued throughout 55 counties as of December 2009. However, cannabis dispensaries within the state accept recommendations, with an embossed license, from a doctor who has given the patient an examination and believes cannabis would be beneficial for their ailment.

[[File:The Green Doctors, Medical Marijuana evaluations, Venice, a beachfront district on the Westside of Los Angeles, California LCCN2013632427.tif|thumb|right|upright=0.85|Cannabis evaluations in [[Venice, Los Angeles#Venice Beach|Venice Beach]]]]
Critics of California's medical cannabis program argued that the program essentially gave cannabis quasi-legality, as "anyone can obtain a recommendation for medical marijuana at any time for practically any ailment".<ref name="History">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/printedition/sunletters/la-oew-gutwillig-imler6-2009mar06,1,7457273,full.story|title=Medical marijuana in California: a history|date=March 6, 2009|work=Los Angeles Times|last2=Gutwillig|first2=Stephen|first1=Scott|last1=Imler|access-date=January 12, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604071650/http://www.latimes.com/news/printedition/sunletters/la-oew-gutwillig-imler6-2009mar06,1,7457273,full.story|archive-date=June 4, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Acknowledging that there were instances in which the system was abused and that laws could be improved, Stephen Gutwillig of the [[Drug Policy Alliance]] insisted that what Proposition 215 had accomplished was "nothing short of incredible".<ref name="History" /> Gutwillig argued that because of the law, 200,000 patients in the state had safe and affordable access to medical cannabis to relieve pain and treat medical conditions, without having to risk arrest or buy off the black market.<ref name="History" />

==== Conflict with federal law ====
Although Proposition 215 legalized medical cannabis in California, at the federal level it remained a [[Schedule I drugs|Schedule I]] prohibited drug.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/identities/2018/8/20/17938372/marijuana-legalization-federal-prohibition-drug-scheduling-system|title=Marijuana is illegal under federal law even in states that legalize it|last=Lopez|first=German|date=2018-08-20|work=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>  Seeking to enforce this prohibition, the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] conducted numerous raids and prosecutions of medical cannabis providers throughout the state in subsequent years. Who grows marijuana and where it comes from were lightly regulated. Federal authorities claimed that these medical marijuana businesses were fronts for the black market. Also rather than growing medical marijuana in small batches for patients, they claimed the cannabis was coming from Mexico or large hidden grows in California.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/11/13/164981433/legalizing-and-regulating-pot-a-growth-industry|title=Legalizing And Regulating Pot: A Growth Industry|last=Dokoupil|first=Tony|date=November 13, 2012|work=NPR News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14|quote=California doesn't have tight regulations on who grows marijuana, where it comes from. So the feds move in, and what they claim is that these med marijuana businesses are fronts for what are in fact just old-school black market drug dealers. And they're not growing medical marijuana in small batches for patients. They're growing it in Mexico, or they're growing it in the hills, and they're just bringing it in, and it suddenly, magically becomes legal once it gets in the store. But in fact, it's based on illegality.}}</ref> Some state and local officials strongly supported these enforcement efforts, in particular Attorney General [[Dan Lungren]] who was a vocal opponent of Proposition 215 leading up to its passage.<ref name="Lee" />  Other officials, such as San Francisco District Attorney [[Terence Hallinan]], condemned the actions as a gross intrusion into the state's affairs.<ref name="Lee" />  The raids and prosecutions increased in frequency throughout the Bush and Obama years,<ref name="WTC">{{citation|title=What's the Cost? {{!}} The Federal War on Patients|url=https://american-safe-access.s3.amazonaws.com/documents/WhatsTheCost.pdf|access-date=April 29, 2017|publisher=Americans for Safe Access|date=June 2013}}</ref> until finally in December 2014 the [[Rohrabacher–Farr amendment]] was enacted at the federal level.

One of the raids that occurred was at the [[Wo/Men's Alliance for Medical Marijuana]] in Santa Cruz in September 2002. WAMM was a non-profit collective set up to provide cannabis to seriously ill patients, and was working closely with local authorities to follow all applicable state and local laws.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berry|first1=Denis|title=City leaders stand behind Medical Marijuana at City Hall|url=http://www.drugpolicy.org/news/2002/09/city-leaders-stand-behind-medical-marijuana-city-hall|access-date=February 24, 2018|work=Drug Policy Alliance|date=September 12, 2002|archive-date=February 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224232634/http://www.drugpolicy.org/news/2002/09/city-leaders-stand-behind-medical-marijuana-city-hall|url-status=dead}}</ref> On the morning of September 5, DEA agents equipped with paramilitary gear and semiautomatic weapons stormed the premises, destroyed all the cannabis plants, and arrested the property owners Mike and Valerie Corral.<ref name="Lee" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gardner|first1=Fred|title=The Raid on WAMM|url=http://www.beyondthc.com/the-raid-on-wamm/|access-date=March 6, 2018|work=O'Shaughnessy's|date=September 2002}}</ref> This prompted an angry response from nearby medical cannabis patients{{snd}}some in wheelchairs{{snd}}who gathered at the site to block federal agents from leaving, until finally after three hours later the Corrals were released.<ref name="Lee" /> The raid triggered a strong backlash from Santa Cruz city officials as well, who sanctioned an event two weeks later where cannabis was handed out to patients on the steps of city hall,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Leduff|first1=Charlie|last2=Liptak|first2=Adam|title=Defiant California City Hands Out Marijuana|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/18/us/defiant-california-city-hands-out-marijuana.html|access-date=February 24, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=September 18, 2002}}</ref> attracting widespread media attention.<ref name="Heddleston" />  The DEA was "appalled" by the event,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gaura|first1=Maria Alicia|last2=Stannard|first2=Matthew B.|title=Santa Cruz officials to defy feds, hand out medical pot at City Hall|url=https://www.sfgate.com/health/article/Santa-Cruz-officials-to-defy-feds-hand-out-2771085.php|access-date=February 24, 2018|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=September 13, 2002}}</ref> but took no further action.

Further pushback against federal enforcement efforts occurred in June 2003 following the jury trial conviction of [[Ed Rosenthal]], who had been raided by the DEA in 2002 for growing more than 100 cannabis plants in an [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] warehouse.<ref name="rosenthal">{{cite news|last1=Baily|first1=Eric|last2=Rodriguez|first2=Marcelo|title=The 'Guru of Ganja' Gets a Day in Jail|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2003-jun-05-me-guru5-story.html|access-date=February 28, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 5, 2003}}</ref>  Because cannabis remained a prohibited substance under federal law, jurors could not be informed that Rosenthal had been deputized by the city of Oakland to grow the cannabis, or even that the cannabis was being used for medical purposes only.<ref name="Lee">{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Martin A.|title=Smoke Signals: A Social History of Marijuana – Medical, Recreational, and Scientific|date=August 2012|publisher=Scribner|location=New York|isbn=978-1439102602}}</ref>  Rosenthal was easily convicted as a result; however, immediately following the trial, when jurors found out the true circumstances of the case, they publicly renounced the verdict they had just handed down and demanded a retrial.<ref name="Lee" />  Judge [[Charles R. Breyer|Charles Breyer]], in part influenced by the extraordinary action of the jurors, sentenced Rosenthal to just one day in jail, of which he had already served.<ref name="rosenthal" />

In July 2007, a new tactic was adopted by the DEA of threatening landlords renting to medical cannabis providers.<ref>{{citation|last1=Eddy|first1=Mark|title=Medical Marijuana: Review and Analysis of Federal and State Policies|url=https://medicalmarijuana.procon.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/37/medicalmarjiuanastatepolicies040210.pdf|publisher=Congressional Research Service|date=April 2, 2010}}</ref>  Letters were sent to a number of property owners in the Los Angeles area, informing them that they faced up to 20 years in prison for violating the "crack house statute" of the Controlled Substances Act, in addition to seizure of their properties.  This tactic subsequently spread to other areas of California, while DEA raids continued to increase as well in the following years.  In October 2011 an extensive and coordinated crackdown on California's cannabis dispensaries was announced by the chief prosecutors of the state's four federal districts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/la-xpm-2011-oct-07-la-me-obama-medical-marijuana-20111008-story.html|title=Federal crackdown on medical pot sales reflects a shift in policy|last=Hoeffel|first=John|date=October 7, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>

Three major court cases originated in California that attempted to challenge the federal government's ability to enforce federal law in states that have legalized medical cannabis.  ''[[Conant v. McCaffrey]]'' was brought forth in response to various threats made by the federal government against doctors who recommend cannabis to patients.  Decided in 2000, it upheld the right of physicians to recommend but not prescribe cannabis.<ref name="mpp">{{citation|title=State-By-State Medical Marijuana Laws|url=https://www.mpp.org/assets/pdf/issues/medical-marijuana/State-by-State-Laws-Report-2015.pdf|publisher=Marijuana Policy Project|date=December 2016}}</ref>  In ''[[United States v. Oakland Cannabis Buyers' Cooperative]]'' (decided in 2001), it was argued that medical use of cannabis should be permitted as constituted by a "[[medical necessity]]"{{snd}}but this argument was unsuccessful.<ref name="mpp" />  In ''[[Gonzales v. Raich]]'' (decided in 2005), the constitutionality of the Controlled Substances Act was challenged based on the idea that cannabis grown and consumed in California does not qualify as [[interstate commerce]]{{snd}}but this argument was also found to be without merit.<ref name="mpp" />

=== Recreational cannabis legalization ===
==== Proposition 19 (1972) ====
{{main|California Proposition 19 (1972)}}
In 1972, California became the first state to vote on a ballot measure seeking to legalize cannabis.  Proposition 19{{snd}}the California Marijuana Initiative{{snd}}sought to legalize the use, possession, and cultivation of cannabis, but did not allow for commercial sales.<ref name="Anderson">{{cite book|last1=Anderson|first1=Patrick|title=High In America: The True Story Behind NORML And The Politics Of Marijuana|date=February 27, 1981|publisher=The Viking Press|isbn=978-0670119905|url=http://www.druglibrary.org/special/anderson/highinamerica.htm}}</ref>  The initiative was spearheaded by the group Amorphia, which was founded in 1969 (by Blair Newman) and financed its activities through the sale of hemp [[rolling paper]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dufton|first1=Emily|title=Grass Roots: The Rise and Fall and Rise of Marijuana in America|date=December 5, 2017|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=978-0465096169}}</ref>  It was ultimately defeated by a wide margin (33–67%), but supporters were encouraged by the results,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sinclair|first1=John|title=Getting NORML {{!}} A brief history of the movement to legalize marijuana|url=https://www.metrotimes.com/detroit/getting-norml/Content?oid=2150635|access-date=February 11, 2018|work=Detroit Metro Times|date=October 27, 2010}}</ref> which provided momentum to other reform efforts in California in subsequent years.<ref name="Heddleston" />  In 1974, Amorphia ran into financial difficulties and became the California chapter of [[National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws|NORML]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Mission|url=http://www.canorml.org/canormlmission.html|website=California NORML|access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>

==== Marijuana Control, Regulation, and Education Act (2009) ====
{{main|Marijuana Control, Regulation, and Education Act}}
In February 2009, [[Tom Ammiano]] introduced the Marijuana Control, Regulation, and Education Act, which would remove penalties under state law for the cultivation, possession, and use of marijuana for persons the age of 21 or older. When the Assembly Public Safety Committee approved the bill on a 4 to 3 vote in January 2010, this marked the first time in United States history that a bill legalizing marijuana passed a legislative committee. While the legislation failed to reach the Assembly floor, Ammiano stated his plans to reintroduce the bill later in the year, depending on the success of [[California Proposition 19 (2010)|Proposition 19]], the Regulate, Control and Tax Cannabis Act.<ref name="banks1">{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2010-mar-29-la-me-banks30-2010mar30-story.html|title=Pot breaks the age barrier|last=Banks|first=Sandy|date=March 29, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=March 31, 2010}}</ref> According to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', California tax collectors estimated the bill would have raised about $1.3 billion a year in revenue.

Critics such as John Lovell, lobbyist for the California Peace Officers' Association, argued that too many people already struggle with alcohol and drug abuse, and legalizing another mind-altering substance would lead to a surge of use, making problems worse.<ref name="Time">{{cite magazine|url=http://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1884956,00.html|title=Can Marijuana Help Rescue California's Economy?|last=Stateman|first=Alison|date=March 13, 2009|magazine=Time|access-date=May 24, 2021}}</ref> Apart from helping the state's budget by enforcing a tax on the sale of cannabis, proponents of the bill argued that legalization would reduce the amount of criminal activity associated with the drug.

==== Proposition 19 (2010) ====
{{main|California Proposition 19 (2010)}}
In November 2010, California voters rejected Proposition 19 (by a vote of 53.5% to 46.5%), an initiative that would have legalized the use, possession, and cultivation of cannabis for adults age 21 and over, and regulated its sale similar to alcohol.<ref>{{cite news|title=California Proposition 19, the Marijuana Legalization Initiative (2010)|url=https://ballotpedia.org/California_Proposition_19,_the_Marijuana_Legalization_Initiative_(2010)|website=Ballotpedia|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>  The initiative faced stiff opposition from numerous police organizations in the state, while many growers in the [[Emerald Triangle]] were strongly opposed due to fears that corporate megafarms would put them out of business.<ref name="Lee" />  The initiative was also undercut by the passage of [[#Senate Bill 1449 (2010)|Senate Bill 1449]] a month before the election.<ref name="Lee" />  Proposition 19 was spearheaded by [[Richard Lee (activist)|Richard Lee]], founder of [[Oaksterdam University]].<ref name="Lee" />

==== Proposition 64 (2016) ====
{{main|Adult Use of Marijuana Act}}
[[File:2016 California Proposition 64 results map by county.svg|thumb|right|275px|[[Adult Use of Marijuana Act|Proposition 64 (2016)]] results by county. Counties with a majority of "yes" votes are in blue and counties with a majority of "no" votes are in yellow.]]
[[File:High Times - Coalinga - October 2022 - Sarah Stierch.jpg|thumb|right|High Times cannabis dispensary in [[Coalinga]], California, pictured in October 2022 (Sarah Stierch ([https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ CC BY 4.0]))]]
On November 8, 2016, Proposition 64{{snd}}the Adult Use of Marijuana Act{{snd}}passed by a 57% to 43% vote, legalizing the use, sale, and cultivation of recreational cannabis in California for adults 21 and over. The initiative was certified for the ballot on June 28, 2016,<ref>{{cite news |last1=McGreevy |first1=Patrick |title=Initiative to legalize recreational use of pot in California qualifies for November ballot |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-pot-initiative-snap--20160628-snap-story.html |access-date=May 18, 2021 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=June 28, 2016}}</ref> after supporters handed in more than 600,000 raw signatures of the 365,000 certified signatures that were required.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leff |first1=Lisa |title=Pot legalization backers kick off California campaign |url=https://apnews.com/article/e7c5f794155f4fc3a813e874ff1c769d |access-date=May 18, 2021 |work=Associated Press |date=May 4, 2016}}</ref> The initiative received the largest amount of support from Napster founder [[Sean Parker]] who contributed more than $8.6 million of the $25 million that was raised in support of the initiative.<ref name="bp64">{{cite web |title=California Proposition 64, Marijuana Legalization (2016) |url=https://ballotpedia.org/California_Proposition_64,_Marijuana_Legalization_(2016) |website=Ballotpedia |access-date=May 18, 2021}}</ref> Lieutenant Governor [[Gavin Newsom]] was the highest-ranking official in the state to endorse the initiative;<ref name="bp64" /> it was also endorsed by several of the state's major newspapers including the [[Los Angeles Times]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Editorial: It's time to legalize and regulate marijuana in California. Yes on Proposition 64. |url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-proposition-64-20160918-snap-story.html |access-date=May 18, 2021 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=September 16, 2016}}</ref> [[San Francisco Chronicle]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Chronicle recommends: Legalize marijuana Yes on Prop. 64 |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/editorials/article/Chronicle-recommends-Legalize-marijuana-Yes-on-9223733.php |access-date=May 18, 2021 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=September 15, 2016}}</ref> [[San Diego Union-Tribune]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Yes on Prop. 64: California should legalize marijuana |url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/endorsements/sd-yes-prop-64-legalize-recreational-marijuana-20161026-story.html |access-date=May 18, 2021 |work=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=October 27, 2016}}</ref> [[Orange County Register]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Yes on Proposition 64 |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2016/10/05/yes-on-proposition-64/ |access-date=May 18, 2021 |work=Orange County Register |date=October 5, 2016}}</ref> and [[The Mercury News|San Jose Mercury News]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Editorial: California should legalize recreational marijuana |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2016/08/05/editorial-california-should-legalize-recreational-marijuana/ |access-date=May 18, 2021 |work=San Jose Mercury News |date=August 5, 2016}}</ref>

Immediately upon certification of the November 2016 ballot results, adults age 21 or older were allowed to:
* Possess, transport, process, purchase, obtain, or give away, without any compensation whatsoever, no more than one ounce of dry cannabis or eight grams concentrated cannabis to adults the age of 21 or older.
* Possess, plant, cultivate, harvest, dry, or process no more than six live plants and the produce of those plants in a private residence, in a locked area not seen from normal view, in compliance with all local ordinances.
* Smoke or ingest cannabis.
* Possess, transport, purchase, obtain, use, manufacture, or give away marijuana paraphernalia to peoples the age of 21 or older.
Users may not:
* Smoke it where tobacco is prohibited.
* Possess, ingest or smoke within {{convert|1,000|ft|m}} of a day care, school, or youth center while children are present (except within a private residence and if said smoke is not detectable to said children).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-10-10/gov-newsom-signs-new-law-allowing-medical-marijuana-at-k12-schools|title=Medical marijuana OK at K-12 schools in California after Gov. Newsom signs new law|last=MCGREEVY|first=PATRICK|date=2019-10-10|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>
* Manufacture concentrated cannabis using a volatile solvent without a license under Chapter 3.5 of Division 8 or Division 10 of the Business and Professions Code.
* Possess an open container or marijuana paraphernalia while in the driver or passenger seat of a vehicle used for transportation.
* Smoke or ingest marijuana while operating a vehicle used for transportation.
* Smoke or ingest marijuana while riding in the passenger seat or compartment of a vehicle.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |title=Adult Use of Marijuana Act |url=http://www.yeson64.org/pdfs/AUMA.Amended.12.7.15.Final.pdf |website=yeson64.org |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313213532/http://www.yeson64.org/pdfs/AUMA.Amended.12.7.15.Final.pdf |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

Licenses were issued to allow cultivation and business establishment beginning in 2018. Legal sales for non-medical use were allowed by law beginning January 1, 2018, following formulation of new regulations on retail market by the state's Bureau of Medical Cannabis Regulation (to be renamed Bureau of Marijuana Control).<ref>{{citation|title="Building the airplane while it's being flown": How California looks to build $7B legal pot economy|publisher=Associated Press|date=January 30, 2017|author1=Michael R. Blood |author2=Don Thomson|work=The Cannabist |url=http://www.thecannabist.co/2017/01/30/california-marijuana-legal-economy/72444/}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|date=January 18, 2017|title=California's pot czar on upcoming marijuana regulation: "We will not fail"|newspaper=Sacramento Bee|author=Peter Hecht|url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/california/california-weed/article127368214.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221111423/http://www.sacbee.com/news/state/california/california-weed/article127368214.html|archive-date=February 21, 2017}}</ref>

Proposition 64 is not meant in any way to affect, amend, or restrict the statutes provided for medical cannabis in California under Proposition 215.<ref name=autogenerated1 />

In 2016, in response to Proposition 64, State Treasurer [[John Chiang (California politician)|John Chiang]] set up a working group to explore access to financial services for legal marijuana-related businesses operating in California,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kiel|first1=Matt S.|title=Financing California's Cannabis Businesses: Public Banking Model as a State-Level Solution|url=https://www.natlawreview.com/article/financing-california-s-cannabis-businesses-public-banking-model-state-level-solution|access-date=11 October 2017|work=The National Law Review|publisher=Wilson Elser|date=10 August 2017}}</ref> as access to banking services has been a problem due to the additional burdens mandated by the [[Financial Crimes Enforcement Network|Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)]] on financial institutions to assure that any marijuana related business clients are in compliance with all state laws.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Black|first1=Lester|title=The Credit Unions and Small Banks That Solved the Cannabis Cash Crisis|url=http://www.thestranger.com/green-guide-spring-2017/2017/04/19/25083313/the-credit-unions-and-small-banks-that-solved-the-cannabis-cash-crisis|access-date=11 October 2017|work=The Stranger|date=19 April 2017}}</ref>

=== Post-legalization ===
==== Cannabis Appellations Program (2021) ====
After the adoption of Proposition 64, California has been pioneering<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Moreau|first1=Jean-Baptiste|url=https://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/content/download/341940/3351816/version/1/file/210505+Rapport+cannabis+recreatif.pdf|title=Rapport d'étape sur le cannabis récréatif, établi par la Mission d'Information Commune de l'Assemblée Nationale sur la règlementation et l'impact des différents usages du cannabis|last2=Janvier|first2=Caroline|publisher=[[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]|date=2021-05-05|location=[[Paris]] ([[France]])|pages=208|language=fr}}</ref> the CalCannabis Appellations Project (CAP),<ref>{{Cite web|title=CalCannabis Appellations Project Fact Sheet|url=https://static.cdfa.ca.gov/MCCP/document/P45_Appellation%20Fact_Sheet_ADA.pdf|website=[[California Department of Food and Agriculture]]|access-date=May 30, 2021|archive-date=December 12, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211212165721/https://static.cdfa.ca.gov/MCCP/document/P45_Appellation%20Fact_Sheet_ADA.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref> to develop [[Appellation of origin|appellations of origin]] for cannabis products.<ref>{{Cite web|title=CDFA Releases the Proposed Regulations for the Cannabis Appellations Program {{!}} Cannabis|url=https://cannabis.ca.gov/2020/02/20/cdfa-releases-the-proposed-regulations-for-the-cannabis-appellations-program/|access-date=2021-05-30|language=en|archive-date=June 2, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210602213619/https://cannabis.ca.gov/2020/02/20/cdfa-releases-the-proposed-regulations-for-the-cannabis-appellations-program/|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[California Department of Food and Agriculture]] claims that the CAP will "promote regional cannabis goods and local businesses, prevent the misrepresentation of a cannabis good’s origin, and support consumer confidence about a cannabis good’s origin and characteristics."<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=CDFA - CalCannabis - CalCannabis Appellations Project|url=https://www.cdfa.ca.gov/calcannabis/appellations.html|access-date=2021-05-30|website=www.cdfa.ca.gov}}</ref> A series of consultations are underway to develop the CAP.<ref name=":0" />

The benefits of this program:<ref>{{Cite web |title=California Marijuana Laws {{!}} CaliforniaCannabis.org |url=https://californiacannabis.org/laws |access-date=2023-01-23 |website=California Cannabis Information Portal |language=en-US}}</ref>

# Promoting the unique characteristics and qualities of cannabis grown in different regions, similar to how wine regions are known for specific varietals and styles.
# Encouraging sustainable and responsible farming practices by requiring growers in designated regions to meet certain environmental and labor standards.<ref>{{Cite web |title=CDFA CANNABIS APPELLATIONS PROGRAM |url=https://www.cdfa.ca.gov/oefi/cap/docs/cap_flyer_2022.pdf}}</ref>
# Supporting small farmers and preserving local agriculture by promoting and protecting the unique heritage of cannabis grown in specific regions.
# Provide consumers with more information about the origin and quality of cannabis products, similar to how wine bottles are labeled with their region of origin.
# Help to establish California as a leader in the cannabis industry<ref>{{Cite web |title=Cannabis social equity assessment |url=https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/dam/sdc/cao/oerj/cannabis-social-equity-assessment.pdf}}</ref> by setting standards for high-quality cannabis production.
# Create economic opportunities for rural communities and help them to diversify their income sources
# Promote transparency, traceability, and accountability in the cannabis supply chain by providing a means to certify the origin and quality of cannabis products.

==== September 2022 reforms ====
In September 2022, Governor Gavin Newsom signed into law a number of cannabis-related reforms, including bills to protect cannabis users from healthcare discrimination,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jaeger |first1=Kyle |title=California Governor Signs Bill Protecting Medical Cannabis Patients From Healthcare Discrimination |url=https://www.marijuanamoment.net/california-governor-signs-bill-protecting-medical-cannabis-patients-from-healthcare-discrimination/ |access-date=September 28, 2022 |work=Marijuana Moment |date=September 5, 2022}}</ref> require child welfare social workers to treat parental cannabis use the same as alcohol,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jaeger |first1=Kyle |title=California Governor Signs Child Welfare Bill Treating Parental Marijuana Use Just Like Alcohol |url=https://www.marijuanamoment.net/california-governor-signs-child-welfare-bill-treating-parental-marijuana-use-just-like-alcohol/ |access-date=September 28, 2022 |work=Marijuana Moment |date=September 7, 2022}}</ref> prevent employees from being fired for cannabis use outside of work hours (with exceptions for federal employees or workers in safety-sensitive positions),<ref name="ten">{{cite news |last1=Jaeger |first1=Kyle |title=California Governor Signs 10 Marijuana Bills, Including Interstate Commerce, Employment Protections And Record Sealing |url=https://www.marijuanamoment.net/california-governor-signs-10-marijuana-bills-including-interstate-commerce-employment-protections-and-record-sealing/ |access-date=September 28, 2022 |work=Marijuana Moment |date=September 18, 2022}}</ref> allow veterinarians to recommend medical cannabis for pets,<ref name="ten" /> facilitate the sealing of records for certain cannabis offenses,<ref name="ten" /> and allow interstate commerce for cannabis to and from California (provided that the federal government has first indicated that it will allow such activity).<ref name="ten" />

====Pesticide contamination====
In June 2024, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' tested legally-sold cannabis products in California and uncovered large amounts of pesticides in many  cannabis products.   Twenty-five of 42 products contained pesticides exceeding the levels permitted by law.  The investigation alleges that many testing laboratories fraudulently certified products as satisfying pesticide regulations, when in fact they did not meet the regulations. Owners of some private testing laboratories stated that they were forced out of business because they refused to falsify test results.  The Department of Cannabis Control, which is responsible for regulating cannabis in California, refused to release the results of its own internal testing of cannabis products.  In September 2024, a lawsuit was filed by a former employee of the Department of Cannabis Control, alleging that the head of the department had ignored fraudulent testing, and that the department fired the former employee  when the employee attempted to publicize the fraud.<ref name="tumult">
